AB  - An acidophilic metal-resistant bacterial strain, Acidomyces
acidothermus (A. acidothermus), was isolated and identified by
morphology, physiology, biochemistry, and 16S rDNA. A. acidothermus
culture conditions were optimized by response surface methodology
(RSM). Results showed that with a temperature of 40 °C, a pH of 3 in a
9k medium, and a rotation speed of 140 r/min, the copper leaching rate
reached the highest value of 39.8%. Furthermore, SEM images and a
heatmap of differential metabolites indicated that A. acidothermus
adsorbed on the surface of WPCBs and extracellular polymeric
substances (EPS), mainly D-glucuronic acid, were secreted, suggesting
the highly efficient mechanism of copper recovery from WPCBs.
