AB  - The recycling of printed circuit boards (PCBs) causes environmental
problems by releasing dioxins and furans. The objective of this study
is the recovery of copper from PCBs through the bioleaching process
using Aspergillus niger which was isolated from the surface of Abu
Tartur phosphate. In the bioleaching process, the optimum conditions
were used to modify ammonium medium with inoculum spore size are 2Χ106
SFU/50 ml for 5 days at 30ͦ C in a pulp of 0.5% solid 150 mesh
particle size and aeration at 200 rpm. Different carbon and nitrogen
sources were used. Glucose (1.5%) and ammonium chloride (0.2%) were
the best source of carbon and nitrogen, respectively. Also, the
optimum initial medium’s pH was 7. At these conditions, about 100% of
Cu was extracted. The mechanism of bioleaching was studied by
detecting the production of organic acid through using brome cresol
green as an indicator and HPLC analysis. The color change of agar
medium of the incubated plate with A. niger from blue to yellow, and
HPLC analysis showed detection malic and citric acids in the sample in
presence e-waste higher than the sample without e-waste. E-waste
before and after the bioleaching process was investigated using SEM.
The surface of e-waste becomes more smooth and porous due to the
bioleaching process.
