AB  - & Bioleaching of Rare Earth ElementsRare earth elements (REEs) are
increasingly important for a variety of technologies.However,
conventional extraction of REEs from monazite, one of the main REE
ores used commercially, requires high energy inputs, and produces
environmentally damaging waste streams.Solubilization of thorium, a
radioactive element which commonly co-occurs with REEs in monazite
ore, is also of concern.In this study, Brisson and coworkers
investigate bioleaching of REEs from monazite sand as a potential
alternative to conventional extraction.They characterize the
bioleaching performance of two newly isolated fungal strains, along
with one strain from a culture collection.The results indicate that
compounds released into solution by the fungi contribute to
bioleaching.Bioleaching also preferentially releases REEs over
radioactive Thorium, leaving Thorium in the solid residual.These
results indicate that bioleaching may provide a promising alternative
to conventional REE extraction, and further study should be done to
understand and optimize the bioleaching process.
